I'm a commercial diver.  I worked three years as a contract diver for TVA (Tennesee Valley Authority).  I've dove on dams, coal plants and nuclear plants.<br>
<br>
The cleanest power source- <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> water</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.  But you can't build a dam just anywhere, so hydro power's very limited.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Coal</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->- nasty nasty nasty.  Ash ponds suck.  Over time, the pipes that carry the ash across the river from the plant, clogs and needs to be replaced.  So I go down and bust 'em apart, releasing some sludgy ash into the river and into my wetsuit (armpits and buttcrack).  Lovely.  The drive through car wash near the plant exit gives you an idea of how clean coal burning is.  Looking into the furnace port holes (if it's not completely covered in soot) you can see the thick black smoke swirling around in there.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Nuke power</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->- one of my favorites.<br>
First some facts as taught in RadTraining, required for un-escorted access to a nuclear plant:<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> 1.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> 650+ mRem causes severe cell damage and kills you.<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> 2.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> plant limits per person/per year- 1 Rem, or 2 Rem with written extension for required purposes.  <br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> 3.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> federal limit per person/per year- 5 Rem.  Exceding it costs the plant $500,000.00<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> 4.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> limit per job should not exceed 250 mRem without permission.<br>
<br>
Now the fun stuff.  As a diver, I've been in places in a nuke plant that noone else has.  I've swam in the reactor (not active of course), I've doggy paddled in spent fuel pools, and I've dove four hour dives, everyday, for 1 1/2 months at a time, in suppression pools and taurus'.<br>
I was involved in a dive one time in a spent fuel pool, that caused an NRC federal 'situation'.  The pool wasn't monitored as planned and our diver ventured into range of a fuel rod's glow coming through the four foot thick concrete barrier.  He was six feet or so away from a 10,000 Rem zone.  Thanks to dosimitry alarms, he only picked up 500 mRem in about 2 seconds.  Luckily, water drastically reduces levels of radiation over short distance.<br>
But despite that little incident, nothing bad has happened.  I am regularly around 100-250 mRem levels, and I my physicals are fine.  We'll see how I am twenty years from now, but I don't feel these levels will result in any problems.<br>
Nuclear plants are regulated so strictly by the NRC, it's almost like the NRC is against the plant operators.  They're just waiting for them to screw up and bust 'em.   They keep tight control of contaminated products.  And the hour glass towers (like on the Simpsons) only emit clean steam from cooling water.<br>
Contamination isn't as bad as it sounds.  I've been contaminated a couple times and usually duct tape took care of it.  Yup, yet another use for duct tape.  And area contaminations have measures for being cleaned up.<br>
<br>
I'm not sure I made the point I was shooting for.  Nuke plants aren't as scary as the eco-nuts like to think.  While high radiation could kill you, the low doses most sources quote as dangerous, I face all the time.  I eat 100 mRem for breakfast,  just to start my day!  And I don't have any side effects, other than this sixth finger and my memory.  <br>
